<TEXT>
an unusual financial arrangement devised to 
promote conservation in the third world could help eastern europe 
begin to repair its badly damaged environment a us lawmaker says 
rep john lafalce dny has proposed in a letter to president 
bush that the united states initiate socalled debtfornature 
swaps with eastern europe to clean up what lafalce said could be 
the final and longest lasting legacy of the stalinist period 
under his proposal the eastern european countries debts to the 
united states would be forgiven in exchange for their commitment to 
redirect the savings to cleaning up their environment 
lafalce also proposed that a multinational environmental trust 
fund be set up for eastern europe 
the problems seem to be very severe said peter preuss a 
toxicologist at the environmental protection agency who recently 
visited poland and hungary 
preuss explained for example that the water in the vistula 
river at krakow poland is not only undrinkable its too dirty for 
industrial use 
it is so salty and acid that the industries along the river 
cant even use it for cooling water preuss said 
levels of air pollutants are many times higher tens of times 
higher than anything found in the united states he said 
in the small blackened town of copsa mica romania every 
building tree and patch of ground is covered with soot and dust 
from factories that dye rubber and produce nonferrous metals 
in january lafalce a senior member of the house banking 
committee and chairman of the house committee on small business 
led a congressional delegation to yugoslavia poland east germany 
hungary and czechoslovakia 
the plan was to discuss trade investment and business with 
eastern european officials but intruding into our discussions of 
all these issues was the problem of environmental degradation 
lafalce said 
on our trip to central europe we saw great hope and great 
expectations he said in his letter to the president but we 
also saw polluted rivers and the dull gray hazy hues of polluted 
skies 
indeed the problems are daunting and can barely be 
exaggerated he wrote 
in the upper silesia region of poland researchers have observed 
an increase in mental retardation because of metal particulates in 
the air 
life expectancy is decreasing in hungary and mothers are 
protesting about the respiratory problems that polluted air is 
causing their children lafalce said 
lafalces staff said legislation to provide for the debt swaps 
and the trust fund to be administered by the new central european 
bank for reconstruction and development will be introduced in 
april 
debt swaps for conservation have been used to encourage third 
world countries to establish nature preserves and to devote 
resources to conservation 
the first such swap was executed in july 1987 by a washington 
environmental organization called conservation international which 
purchased and forgave 650000 of bolivias foreign debt in 
exchange for the establishment of a wildlife preserve the 
arrangement has been widely imitated by other environmental groups 
polands foreign debt is about 40 billion of which 3 billion 
is owed to the united states poland has not made any payments on 
the debt in recent years lafalce said 
hungary on the other hand owes most of its outside debt to 
commercial banks not governments lafalce said if governments 
forgive debt to finance environmental cleanup projects banks 
might do the same he said 
he has proposed that up to 20 billion be put into an 
environmental trust fund under the auspices of the central european 
bank for reconstruction and development about 10 percent of that 
or 2 billion would come from the united states 
the encouragement of environmental cleanup projects in eastern 
europe could benefit american business lafalce said 
businesses in the united states have the experience and 
technology needed to deal with these problems he said 
therefore they could expect to play a leading role in 
establishing the necessary water and sewage treatment and other 
facilities required to solve the problems 
</TEXT>
