<TEXT>
a private school as negligent in the death 
of a teenage student during a schoolsponsored climb of mount hood 
in 1986 that claimed nine lives and should pay the boys father 
500000 a jury decided thursday 
but the multonomah county circuit court jury cleared mountain 
guide ralph summers of negligence for his part in helping lead the 
13member oregon episcopal school party up the mountain 
sixteenyearold richard haeder jr was one of the nine who died 
after the group became lost in a blizzard during the may 1986 
climb summers was among the four who survived 
the verdict on the lawsuit by haeders father richard came 
after about five hours of deliberations 
im happy to have justice done the elder haeder said after 
the verdict if nothing else comes out of this it is that my son 
did not die in vain 
haeder said much of the 500000 award would go toward creating 
scholarships or other funds to honor his son it isnt the 
money he said i wanted everyone to know those deaths were 
needless 
neither summers nor representatives of the school would comment 
the lawsuit accused the school and summers of negligence in 
planning and carrying out the trip 
the climbers tried to reach the top of the 11235foot mountain 
in deteriorating weather got lost in the blizzard as they 
retreated and had to build a snow cave for shelter as the sun set 
the next morning summers and a student hiked to safety and 
notified authorities the snow cave wasnt marked however and 
authorities searched for two days before they found it of the nine 
students and two faculty members inside only two teenagers 
survived 
the jury began deliberating about 2 pm after closing arguments 
in the case 
haeders attorney paul luvera told jurors they were leading 
a group of schoolchildren up a mountain for no good reason this 
wasnt a group of mountain climbers they were schoolchildren 
richie was crying he wanted to go back and they kept going 
luvera said and then he died a horrible painful death with 
people dying all around him in a tomb made of ice 
calling the lawsuit richard and judith haeders final eulogy 
to their son luvera asked that jurors award them 276 million 
luvera said evidence and testimony in the case showed summers 
didnt follow a correct compass bearing or use a map while 
descending the mountain through a snowstorm 
they were lost coming down lost when they dug the snow cave 
and lost the next day when they went for help he said 
he also said summers told inconsistent stories about who was 
leading the climb he or the rev thomas goman both men failed to 
adequately respect the weather and went too far up the mountain 
he said 
attorney mark wagner representing summers and the school told 
the jury to remember the storm that struck the mountain was three 
times stronger than had been predicted 
people died because a storm came in before our people got off 
the mountain he said in the real world accidents do happen 
and it doesnt mean people are negligent or at fault 
