<TEXT>
the pennsylvania governors race is 
tipping conventional political wisdom on its ear when it comes to 
the issue of abortion 
democratic gov robert p casey is an unyielding foe of 
abortion contrary to his national party platform caseys chief 
republican challenger state auditor general barbara hafer is 
firmly prochoice a position that puts her at odds with the gop 
national platform 
while leaders of both parties say they can accommodate people on 
both sides of the issue a caseyhafer contest could test the 
loyalties of many rankandfile members in both parties 
its a difficult one for me said natalie schmoyer a 
marketing consultant and prochoice democrat from suburban 
philadelphia i feel very strongly about the choice issue but 
im also a democrat who votes for democrats its a hard 
choice 
caseys and hafers views on abortion have attracted two more 
candidates to the gubernatorial race an antiabortion republican 
and a prochoice democrat campaigning almost exclusively on the 
abortion issue 
the republican 34yearold marguerite luksik has done little 
campaigning but said she felt compelled to run because no one else 
came forward to challenge hafers prochoice stand 
sometimes i think that not defending your principles is the 
worst thing you can do said mrs luksik who runs a home day 
care program for single parents then it looks like you really 
dont believe in them 
prochoice democrat phil berg a 45yearold lawyer said 
caseys opposition to abortion is the only reason he decided to 
challenge the governor berg who calls himself the conscience of 
our party thinks hafer will have a good shot at becoming 
governor if she and casey face off in november 
were in uncharted territory said g terry madonna 
director of the center for politics and public affairs at 
millersville university of pennsylvania 
madonna expects casey 58 and hafer 46 to win their 
respective primaries on may 15 but he said the contests could 
become a barometer of public sentiment on abortion 
the test will be whether the prolife supporters can energize 
their forces for luksik madonna said theres no doubt that 
the prochoice people have galvanized and energized their forces 
while casey signed into law one of the nations most restrictive 
abortion laws last year and the state legislature is 
overwhelmingly antiabortion surveys show many voters lean the 
other way 
a recent poll commissioned by hafer found 50 percent of those 
surveyed felt a woman should have the right to have an abortion 
while 9 percent said abortion should be illegal in all cases 
about 14 percent of the respondents favored abortion only if the 
mothers life was in danger and another 26 percent said abortion 
should be allowed if the mother was in danger and in cases of rape 
or incest 
the telephone survey of 800 registered voters was done in 
midmarch by michiganbased market opinion research and had a 
margin of error of plus or minus 35 percentage points 
patrick killian hafers campaign manager said the results were 
encouraging because they indicate abortion will be the wild card 
in the race 
killians counterpart in the casey camp james carville said 
the results could not be interpreted as support for hafer because 
not all prochoice voters would support her carville said the same 
caveat applied to the prochoice candidacy of berg in the 
democratic primary 
i believe in pennsylvania the vast majority of democrats and 
the vast majority of republicans see abortion as only one issue 
carville said it isnt going to be just an election on 
abortion 
the abortion issue aside casey is a popular firstterm 
incumbent who is credited with keeping his states finances stable 
while many neighboring states run deficits 
hafers campaign has gone through a rough stretch in which she 
was criticized for calling casey a redneck irishman from 
scranton antagonizing blacks with her comments about a black 
state prisons chief and charging personal and political expenses to 
the state 
