<TEXT>
tiananmen square reopened to the public today 
but police remained on guard to stop any attempt to mourn 
protesters killed last year when soldiers stormed the square to 
crush the prodemocracy movement 
the vast plaza was cordoned off on thursday for the qingming 
festival an annual holiday when chinese honor their dead 
overseas dissidents through facsimile transmissions and mailed 
leaflets had urged beijing residents to stroll through tiananmen 
on qingming in memory of those killed in the military crackdown 
last june 
but officials cordoned off the square and held ceremonies in 
which 13000 young people paid homage to chinas revolutionary 
heritage and pledged allegiance to its socialist system 
officials also closed the square for official ceremonies on 
april 1 another day targeted by overseas activists for silent 
protest marches through the symbolic center of last springs 
democracy movement 
schools and factories have warned young people to stay away from 
tiananmen and told them they face punishment if caught involved in 
any kind of protest 
police continued to maintain a heavy presence around the 
100acre square today police vehicles were parked at strategic 
points and dozens of officers were on patrol 
the monument to revolutionary martyrs in the center of the 
square normally open to the public was closed about a dozen 
police officers stood around the monuments perimeter and on its 
steps and another 10 officers sat nearby 
the next key anniversary will be april 15 the day former 
communist party chief hu yaobang a popular reformist died 
his death touched off the demonstrations for democratic reform 
that continued until the june 34 military attack on the city that 
left hundreds and perhaps thousands dead 
