<TEXT>
seventeen soviet lawyers who have watched the 
upheaval in their country from afar for the past seven months are 
heading home today with plenty of ideas for more changes 
some want to help handicapped children and improve soviet 
justice another hopes his soviet rock star client will make 
american audiences forget madonna 
the 17 are the first to participate in an american bar 
association program that placed them as interns in us law firms 
law schools and government offices 
we believe these 17 each selected for having a spark of 
idealism will be among the leading players in the continuing 
debate on soviet reforms said steven raikin the programs 
director 
the soviet visitors in their early 30s said there is a lot to 
like here but found flaws in the american system they do not want 
to duplicate back in the soviet union 
after declaring that the adoption of children in the united 
states works 10 times better than in the soviet union olga 
djujeva frowned while assessing the american juvenile court system 
it works badly because it is structurally and financially 
weak she said this is not how we are going to do it in the 
ussr 
ms djujeva a moscow state university teacher who specializes 
in family law and childrens rights said her experiences at the 
law schools of cornell university in ithaca ny and valparaiso 
university in indiana have given her a renewed commitment to 
change things 
we have no foster parenting in the soviet union we someday 
will and handicapped children we do not see them because they 
are in special institutions in this country handicapped children 
are part of your open society 
the aba program funded by the new yorkbased soros foundation 
and other private donors was created in anticipation of the 
growing opportunities for joint sovietamerican business and to 
foster mutual understanding between lawyers in both countries 
we learned as much about the soviet system as these 17 kids 
learned about ours raikin said historically soviet lawyers 
have not occupied a major role in their society in the last couple 
of years however theres been an explosion of interest among 
soviet lawyers to play a larger role 
raikin added the next couple of years will be crucial 
everythings up for grabs right now the whole legal reform 
agenda 
up for grabs also are potentially lucrative business contacts 
between east and west a fact not lost on valentin blueger who has 
tried to steer his practice in latvia to entertainment and 
international law 
blueger spent his time with the nashville law firm that 
represents the grand ole opry an experience he says will help him 
better represent soviet rock star laima vaikule 
shes like your madonna blueger said of the singer who has 
sold 20 million records in the soviet union and is trying to make 
her mark in the us market 
the potential is great says blueger with a laugh at the 
mention of several soviet athletes now playing in the national 
basketball association 
raikin said the soviet economy is in desperate need of foreign 
investment but not many soviets know how to facilitate such deals 
valentin is a natural dealmaker 
irene mashlenko an employee of the soviet ministry of justice 
in moscow split her time in the united states between the staffs 
of a state attorney in montgomery county md and a defense lawyer 
after seeing both sides i now think that your system of 
punishment is very severe the terms of imprisonment for 
nonviolent crimes are too long 
but one of the most recent criminal trials mashlenko sat through 
ended in acquittal giving her the best evidence that the us 
system of justice is really a just system 
nearly 200 soviet lawyers applied for the program and more than 
100 us law firms and law schools applied to become hosts 
a new competition will begin in june ending with the selection 
next fall of 30 new interns 
