<TEXT>
senate majority leader george j mitchell 
dmaine and six democratic colleagues are off to the soviet union 
today for talks with soviet president mikhail s gorbachev 
lithuania is sure to be on the agenda when the senators see 
gorbachev and other soviet officials 
while the group intends to talk with leaders of the baltic 
republics in leningrad before they head to moscow mitchell said 
they wont try to cross into lithuania which is trying to secede 
from the soviet union 
mitchell said thursday that he and senate minority leader bob 
dole rkan had been assured by visiting foreign minister eduard 
shevardnadze that the soviets want to solve the lithuanian 
situation by negotiation and dialogue 
they have concluded as a matter of policy that a process that 
does not involve the use of force is in their best interest 
mitchell said 
dole said the senators warned shevardnadze that congress might 
retaliate against moscow with trade sanctions and other economic 
pressures if gorbachev uses further military force in seeking to 
quell the lithuanian independence movement 
ive got to believe they clearly understand theres going to 
be a big gap here in our relationship if something happens in 
lithuania or estonia or any other republic dole said 
congress if anything happens is going to go off on its own 
and sen robert byrd dwva urged president bush to take 
action in support of the lithuanians and to make the us 
position clear to shevardnadze 
mitchell said the congressional delegation will travel to berlin 
before going to the soviet union the group returns april 14 
traveling with mitchell are democratic sens bill bradley of new 
jersey tom daschle of south dakota wyche fowler of georgia john 
glenn of ohio jim sasser of tennessee and paul sarbanes of 
maryland 
meantime dole is taking four republican senators and a lone 
democrat sen howard metzenbaum dohio on a swing through the 
