<TEXT>
just as smallpox was wiped out in the 1970s two 
other debilitating diseases polio and guinea worm could be wiped 
out in the near future global health advocates say 
the international task force for disease eradication said 
thursday in a report published by the us centers for disease 
control that eradication of guinea worm disease which strikes 10 
million people a year largely in the third world is feasible 
if the necessary commitment and resources can be mobilized 
and worldwide polio eradication is technically possible by 
2000 the task force said 
but three other global maladies measles tuberculosis and 
leprosy are not now eradicable the task force said citing 
the need for better measles vaccine improved tests for tb and 
leprosy and the social stigma surrounding the latter 
the benchmark in disease eradication came in 1977 when smallpox 
was eliminated from the planet with efforts spurred largely by the 
united states 
people around the world continue to be plagued by guinea worm 
and polio and public and political awareness along with 
increased national and international commitment will be needed 
to eradicate them the task force reported 
whatever priority countries might give to these diseases the 
matter of resources to the countries concerned is often very 
great said dr donald hopkins project director for the task 
force 
the ideal situation he said is one in which the more 
affluent countries have a direct national stake in seeing that a 
disease is eradicated and are helping less affluent countries to 
get rid of it 
the task force launched at the carter center of emory 
university in atlanta includes representatives from the world 
health organization the united nations childrens fund or unicef 
the us centers for disease control and other agencies 
the task forces assessment on eight worldwide diseases 
guinea worm disease infects 10 million a year eradication is 
feasible with commitment and resources the carter center last week 
announced that american cyanimid co donated enough of a 
guineaworm fighting chemical to make eradication possible within 
five years 
polio kills 25000 a year eradication is technically 
possible improved vaccine would help goal to eliminate in 
western hemisphere by years end 
onchocerciasis blinds 340000 a year eradication of disease 
not now feasible but associated blindness could be eliminated 
through control of carrier worms 
yawsendemic syphilis strikes 25 million a year with 
political and financial inertia eradication not feasible now 
rabies kills 52000 a year albeit virtually none in the 
united states eradication not feasible no vaccine for wildanimal 
populations 
measles kills 2 million a year not now eradicable virus very 
infectious and vaccine not effective in youngest infants hopkins 
said he remains somewhat optimistic for the eradication of measles 
which was believed almost wiped out in this country before a 
comeback in the last few years sooner or later an improved 
vaccine is going to be developed he said 
tuberculosis kills 2 million to 3 million a year eradication 
not feasible need improved tests chemotherapy and vaccine 
leprosy strikes more than 11 million a year eradication not 
now feasible need for improved tests and chemotherapy and 
overcoming of social stigma surrounding the disfiguring disease 
