<TEXT>
prime minister toshiki kaifu said today the broad 
trade reforms approved by the united states and japan could be 
painful but will improve living standards 
consumer groups said the changes could hurt community 
development and go against with cultural values however 
speaking at a news conference kaifu said japan must carry out 
its end of the accord announced thursday in washington as a 
responsible member of the international community 
the agreement reached after four days of discussions sets 
forth complex proposals aimed at lowering americas huge 49 
billion trade deficit with japan 
i ask for the understanding and cooperation of the people of 
my country kaifu said 
in the end he said the reforms will improve the lives of the 
japanese 
the talks were unprecedented because they aimed not at boosting 
sales of specific foreign products but at easing barriers to trade 
in both countries 
but the federation of specialty stores associations said in a 
statement it would do its best to prevent the decisions from 
being enforced by keeping close ties with other groups and 
promoting consumer awareness and cooperation 
it focused its attack on the most controversial of the proposed 
japanese reforms revision of a law that protects small retailers 
by restricting the opening of large department stores a process 
that takes about 10 years 
the united states sought abolition of the law contending larger 
stores are more likely to sell foreign products 
kaifu said effects of the revision would be severe but he 
added i believe it is important for me and all of you to think 
of the viewpoint of consumers interests 
the associations statement said however the decision will 
do nothing but weaken minor retailers devastate shopping districts 
and slow economic and cultural development of the community 
the association claims a membership of 50000 small retailers 
nationwide the trade ministry says japan has 16 million retail 
shops with fewer than 50 employees and 800000 tiny 
momandpop stores 
the talks on barriers to trade known as the structural 
impediments initiative began last july until this week they had 
made little headway 
japan said the united states contributed to the trade imbalance 
with its large budget deficit low savings rate shortterm 
corporate planning and weak education system us negotiators 
promised to remedy these problems 
us officials have argued the changes sought in japan would 
benefit japanese consumers who pay some of the worlds highest 
prices as a result of a complex distribution system and numerous 
government restrictions 
japanese consumers however have not formed strong 
organizations to press for change and many japanese identify their 
own interests with those of their companies 
larger is not necessarily better said naokazu takeuchi head of 
the japan consumers union one of the nations largest consumer 
groups 
it is not cheap pricing that we consumers want he said 
we have to take many elements cultural aspects community 
relationship into consideration before making decisions 
kaifu said the promised package of reforms would benefit not 
only the united states and japan but also the whole world serve 
to prevent the rise of protectionism and thus contribute to the 
steady development of the world economy 
the japanese measures included in the interim report have been 
attained after undergoing a difficult domestic process and their 
implementation may in some cases be painful kaifu said it 
is my conviction however that they are essential in furthering 
japans own national interest 
among japans pledges was one to spend more on public works such 
as housing sewers parks airports and port facilities 
the united states believing such spending will boost japans 
demand for foreign goods and services sought a spending target 
but japan said it will decide expenditures annually to avoid 
overheating the economy 
on the retail store law which the united states wanted 
abolished japan said it will improve how the law works revise it 
next year and then review it again in another two years 
if by then it still takes 10 years to open large stores 
specific areas of the country would be exempted from the law 
japanese officials said 
because the agreement said specific areas the law will not 
be abolished an official of the ministry of international trade 
and industry said on condition of anonymity 
