<TEXT>
china has agreed to resume the fulbright scholar 
exchange program with the united states but on a smaller scale a 
us embassy official said today 
china abruptly canceled the 198990 program in august in anger 
over us criticism of the military suppression of the studentled 
movement for democratic reform 
the official speaking on condition of anonymity said a formal 
agreement was reached wednesday with the state education commission 
for the 199091 academic year starting in the fall 
sixteen american professors will come to china and 16 chinese 
scholars will do advanced research at us universities he said 
the 198990 program had called for an exchange of 24 scholars 
from each side with 12 graduate students and 12 research fellows 
representing china it had been one of the largest fulbright 
programs which exchange american and foreign scholars around the 
world 
the chinese government has sharply curtailed approval of 
overseas studies for undergraduates and most graduate students 
since its crackdown on political dissent last spring 
the government while insisting it will continue overseas study 
programs is now limiting scholarships mainly to older scholars in 
technical fields for shortterm programs 
the reasoning is that such scholars will be less likely to 
become involved in politics while abroad and will be less tempted 
to join the thousands of chinese students who have failed to return 
home after completing their programs 
the us embassy in a statement said the fulbright program 
fills a need not addressed in other exchange programs and the 
agreement was a positive step toward the resumption of this 
important program 
it added we hope the chinese will resume the participation of 
chinese graduate students in the near future and will take steps 
in other areas that will be conducive to reform and to chinas 
opening to the outside world 
the exchange of 16 scholars on each side roughly returns the 
program to its size during the 198485 academic year 
discussion on resuming the exchanges began after president bush 
dispatched national security adviser brent scowcroft to beijing in 
december for talks aimed at easing bilateral tensions 
no progress has been made in other areas deemed crucial to 
improved relations 
china is believed to still be holding without trial thousands of 
people who participated in last years democracy movement and it 
has taken a hardline position on the release of astrophysicist and 
political dissident fang lizhi 
fang and his wife li shuxian took refuge in the us embassy 
after the military crackdown in june and have since been charged as 
counterrevolutionaries 
negotiations on their safe passage out of the country have 
apparently stalled with china continuing to insist the two give 
themselves up to chinese authorities and admit their guilt 
the fulbright program was established in 1946 under legislation 
by former sen j william fulbright dark more than 167000 
people including 58000 from the united states and 109000 from 
abroad have participated 
