<TEXT>
funeral services will be monday for jazz 
trombonist louis nelson the last surviving musician from the 
original preservation hall bands 
nelson 87 died thursday from injuries suffered in a car 
accident 10 days earlier 
he was someone who played with the musicians of the last 
century and played almost into the next one said jazz historian 
dick allen 
nelsons last performance was two weeks ago at the palm court 
cafe in the french quarter with his louis nelson all stars he had 
been scheduled to perform this weekend at the french quarter 
festival but complained he had not felt well since another driver 
had collided with his vehicle after running a red light 
although he did not appear seriously injured from the accident 
he collapsed wednesday night and was rushed to a hospital where he 
never recovered 
a funeral will be held monday 
he was the last personal link to the original tailgate 
style allen said thats the way trombonists used to play in 
new orleans sitting on the tailgate of the wagon as they 
advertised dances 
nelson was playing with the kid thomas band in 1961 when 
private jam sessions at a french quarter art gallery became so 
popular that the place was opened as preservation hall dedicated 
to keeping the oldtime music alive 
nelson became an indefatigable international star touring south 
america australia and europe he was booked for a tour of japan in 
august 
at the time of his death he was still playing preservation hall 
twice a week with the kid sheik band as well as leading his own 
band on saturdays 
his style ranged from the unbridled energy of traditional new 
orleans jazz to the sweet lyrical sliding melodies of the swing 
era 
nelson was born in new orleans on sept 17 1902 but grew up in 
napoleonville his mother was a mathematician and a graduate of the 
boston conservatory of music his father was a physician 
in the 1920s he played with the kid harris dixieland band and 
kid rena he was a member of the famed sidney desvignes band for 
15 years including five years playing on a mississippi riverboat 
during the depression he was in the works progress 
administrations big band and during world war ii he was in the 
naval band after the war he joined kid thomas at specks moulin 
rouge in marrero where their harddriving band acheived instant 
fame 
since then he has played with numerous bands including george 
lewis kid howard and billie and dede pierce and made records all 
over the world 
nelson is survived by his daughter anna tircuit of new orleans 
seven grandchildren 14 greatgrandchildren and three 
greatgreatgrandchildren 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

