<TEXT>
about 1000 of the nations newspaper editors 
met here this week to talk shop and look over some political 
leaders footnotes from the meeting of the american society of 
newspaper editors 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
at a time of stagnant newspaper circulation editors worried 
about the challenge of producing a newspaper that simultaneously 
appeals to two groups loyal readers who like to read and are 
deeply interested in the world and the oftenyounger readers or 
nonreaders who grew up on television have little love of 
reading and chiefly want news that will affect their lives 
researcher kris mcgrath who helped write a report on how 
readers look at newspapers put the distinction this way 
in this nation of specialists the daily newspaper habit 
appears to be declining people speak of catching the news rather 
than keeping up with it the preferred way to catch the news 
often is while doing something else listening to the radio while 
driving or watching tv while exercising its hard to do something 
else while reading a newspaper other than drink a cup of coffee 
and coffee consumption is down too 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
housing secretary jack kemp former player for the professional 
buffalo bills football team former congressman and former 
candidate for the 1988 republican presidential nomination gave the 
editors a speech full of the usual kemp evangelism 
he was introduced as a bleedingheart conservative and in 
his speech used the term capitalism with a human face an 
editor accused kemp of benign plagiarism swiping the catchword of 
czechoslvakian communist reformers who were suppresed by soviet 
tanks in 1968 
said the editor you speak of capitalism with a human face 
that actually is a paraphrase of eurocommunism which was 
communism with a human face 
replied kemp im not troubled at all by phrases i can defend 
liberal democratic values in a republican convention so 
phrases dont bother me at all whether im a bleedingheart 
conservative or a progressive conservative or a jeffersonian 
democratic republican so im not afraid at all to say that i 
would support the idea of capitalism with a human face or a 
socially responsible capitalist economy 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
one of the meetings most dramatic moments occurred when leroy 
aarons senior vice president for news at the oakland calif 
tribune ended a report to the editors on the views of homosexual 
journalists by publicly revealing his own sexual orientation 
in a paragraph scribbled at the end of his typewritten text and 
read hurriedly in a choked voice aarons said 
i want you to know that the doing of this report has had 
tremendous impact on gay and lesbian journalists across the nation 
it has given them hope and new optimism it has enhanced their 
respect for this organization i as an editor and a gay man am 
proud of asne 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
aarons reported that the 205 gay journalists who took part in a 
survey felt that coverage of gay and lesbian issues other than 
aids is at best mediocre 
he said newspapers failed to take advantage of the expertise 
that their homosexual staff members could provide 
we dont have to prime the supply pump to get gay and lesbian 
expertise on our staffs it is already there he said they 
may be hiding but they are there eager to be heard 
the point to emphasize here is the link between workplace 
issues and coverage a newsroom in which gay and lesbian staff 
people feel safe and accepted is one in which they will come 
forward and make their case on coverage a workplace is which gays 
and lesbians know they can aspire to management roles even though 
it is known they are gay will be one with enhanced sensitivity to 
these issues in our communities a newsroom where insulting remarks 
are forbidden also becomes a newsroom in which sensitive 
terminology is encoded and enforced 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
david halberstam former pulitzer prizewinning newspaper 
reporter told the editors the way to retain readers is to improve 
their papers he lectured on the danger of paying more attention to 
the bottom line than the printed word 
a newspaper is like an addiction halberstam said you 
have to have it you have to read the sports this section that 
section if you start shrinking it you cut down the addiction 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

