<TEXT>
the soviet union today withdrew its demand 
that a reunified germany be neutral and foreign minister eduard a 
shevardnadze predicted very important documents will be signed 
at next months superpower summit 
but shevardnadze and the white house acknowledged it may not be 
possible to resolve all major provisions of a new treaty to reduce 
longrange nuclear weapons before the arrival of president mikhail 
s gorbachev on may 30 
there are very technical issues that need to be resolved 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said of the strategic arms 
reduction treaty that would cut the most dangerous us and soviet 
nuclear arms 
shevardnadze predicted a wide range of agreements at bushs 
washington summit with gorbachev but he too cautioned that it 
will take an additional effort to settle on ways to cut 
longrange nuclear missiles in time to be initialed by the two 
leaders at the summit 
also soviet actions in breakaway lithuania continued to mar the 
ussoviet relationship fitzwater said the superpower 
relationship is at stake in this matter 
shevardnadze took a conciliatory stance on issues surrounding 
the unification of east germany a soviet ally with west germany 
the linchpin in europe of the north atlantic treaty organization 
we have to look for a solution a solution that would be 
acceptable to both nato and the warsaw pact shevardnadze said 
he could not provide a specific blueprint he said but added it 
is possible we will be able to find a mutally acceptable solution 
earlier secretary of state james a baker iii said the soviets 
had eased off their demand that the merged germany be neutral but 
continued to object to its membership in nato 
this summit certainly will become a major event in world 
affairs shevardnadze told reporters the two presidents will 
sign very important documents 
fitzwater said bush had underscored to shevardnadze that the 
united states did not recognize the soviets incorporation of 
lithuania in 1940 and that the kremlin should not take actions to 
block the baltic republics assertion of independence 
the foreign minister delivered a letter to bush from gorbachev 
that dealt with arms control fitzwater said declining to provide 
any details 
he called the twohour session cordial and productive 
shevardnadze standing under an umbrella in a rainswept 
driveway told reporters agreements in preparation deal with arms 
control trade relations cooperation in science and space 
