<TEXT>
a retailers group said friday it will fight key 
business reforms japan promised the united states to alter the 
nations trade imbalance and a consumer group disputed claims the 
changes would help them 
prime minister toshiki kaifu in a televised appearance asked 
japanese for understanding and cooperation he said the 
economic changes could in some cases be painful but he 
promised they would lead to a better quality of life for the 
japanese people 
under an agreement reached thursday in washington japan 
promised to address wideranging structural barriers to trade the 
most controversial point of the package would revise a japanese law 
that protects small retailers by restricting the opening of larger 
stores 
the federation of specialty stores associations reacted with 
anger this point 
the decision will do nothing but weaken minor retailers 
devastate shopping districts and slow down economic and cultural 
development of the community it said 
under current japanese law consent of small neighboring shops 
is needed before a big store can open the process can take 10 
years 
us officials say the law impedes entry of foreign stores they 
also note that larger japanese stores are more likely to sell 
imported products than small shops 
easing such barriers would help cut the united states 49 
billion trade deficit with japan they say 
the federation vowed to do our best to prevent the decisions 
from being enforced by keeping close ties with other groups and 
promoting consumer awareness and cooperation 
the association claims a membership of 50000 small retailers 
nationwide the trade ministry says japan has 16 million retail 
shops with fewer than 50 employees and 800000 tiny 
momandpop stores 
us officials also have argued that changes sought in japan 
would benefit japanese consumers who pay some of the worlds 
highest prices because of a complex distribution system and a web 
of government restrictions 
but some see advantages to the small stores 
it is not cheap pricing that we consumers want said naokazu 
takeuchi head of the japan consumers union one of the nations 
largest consumer groups he said large supermarkets charge 
relatively high prices for produce that is not necessarily fresh 
a mushrooming of large stores could destroy local shopping 
communities he added 
we have to take many elements cultural aspects community 
relationship into consideration before making decisions 
takeuchi said 
kabun muto minister of international trade and industry said 
it is necessary for us to create an environment that promotes 
sales of imported foreign goods in japan because we are living in 
the era of speed it is only natural to shorten the new store 
approval process 
for small retailers muto said we will never give them 100 
percent protection under our free economy system it is their own 
responsibility to make efforts to make their own business go well 
kaifu called the reforms a duty that japan must discharge as a 
responsible member of the international community 
kaiful said the implementation of the changes may be painful 
it is my conviction however that they are essential in 
furthering japans own national interest he said 
foreign minister taro nakayama said against the background of 
the serious largescale trade imbalance the present japanus 
economic relations unless managed properly is in the danger of 
suffering grave damage posing a threat of undermining the mutual 
trust which lies at the foundation of the overall relationship 
between the two nations 
japan argued in the talks that the united states contributed to 
the trade imbalance with its large budget deficit low savings 
rate shortterm corporate planning and relatively weak education 
system us negotiators promised efforts to remedy these problems 
