<TEXT>
a distraught and unemployed man 
walked into a museum friday and sprayed a chemical on rembrandts 
the night watch but museum officials said damage to the 
nations most famous painting was slight 
it was the third attack this century on the huge rembrandt 
which hangs in the rijksmuseum the painting was slashed in the two 
other incidents 
a museum guard immediately sprayed a neutralizing agent saving 
the artworks delicate paint layer before the chemical could eat 
through the veneer said museum keeper piet van thiel 
by late friday afternoon most of the chemical had been removed 
from the 12by14 foot painting like all governmentowned 
artworks it is not insured its value has never been made public 
the attacker wore a hooded raincoat and was about six feet from 
the painting when he produced a little spray pump he had been 
concealing in his hand said witness barry olshen a professor 
from toronto 
dutch television described the chemical as concentrated sulfuric 
acid 
only a kneehigh steel barrier keeps visitors away from the work 
rembrandt painted in 1642 unarmed guards are near it at all times 
museum guards overpowered the suspect and handed him over to 
police who said they were unable to determine the mans motives 
the 31yearold man was not identified in line with dutch police 
practice he was held on suspicion of vandalism 
hes confused and not telling us anything at the moment 
police spokesman klaas wilting said 
restoration experts took the painting out of its plain wooden 
frame and stood it against the wall on the museums second floor 
where it shares a spacious gallery with three other 17thcentury 
paintings 
using delicate brushes they applied an agent that dried out the 
white blobs covering about a square yard of the work then wiped it 
clean 
van thiel told reporters the painting needs new veneer but will 
go on display in two weeks protected by a glass shield until the 
veneer is dry 
the attack was a reminder how vulnerable the netherlands 
artworks are said rob mulders of the sothebys auction firm 
in 1975 a dutch schoolteacher claiming to be on a divine 
mission slashed the night watch several times with a knife 
stolen from the restaurant where he had just eaten lunch he later 
committed suicide in a mental asylum 
during world war i a jobless shoemaker slashed the painting to 
protest his inability to find work 
the night watch portrays a group of 17thcentury militiamen 
characteristic of the period when such fraternal organizations 
patrolled dutch cities by night 
it is best known for rembrandts skillful handling of light and 
darkness and the beam of light that illuminates a richly dressed 
woman in the foreground 
the painting was believed to have been made on the occasion of a 
1638 visit to amsterdam by maria de medici queen of france 
