<TEXT>
civilian unemployment dipped to 52 percent in 
march a slight improvement from february and the lowest rate in a 
year the government said friday 
but analysts attributed the good news more to a statistical 
quirk than to an economic upswing indeed the labor department 
report said the number of new jobs last month hit a fouryear low 
the economy is muddling along but its muddling along at a 
fullemployment level said robert dederick chief economist for 
the northern trust co of chicago its a stay as you are 
sir economy continuing along its path of steady but sluggish 
growth 
last months 52 percent jobless rate down from februarys 53 
percent was the lowest since march 1989 when the rate was at a 
15year low of 50 percent 
the next month joblessness hit 53 percent then eased down to 
52 percent in may but rose again in june to 53 percent where it 
held through february 
even with fridays report most analysts remained concerned that 
the slowdown in the economys overall growth would translate into 
higher jobless rates by years end 
the low unemployment rate is a surprise in an economy thats 
growing below its potential if we continue to have anemic 
growth its going up said allen sinai chief economist at the 
boston co 
by the end of the year some analysts predicted unemployment 
could reach 57 percent 
taking a more optimistic view michael boskin chairman of the 
presidential council of economic advisers said administration 
officials believe theres room for the economy to expand and for 
employment growth to continue and the economy to grow more strongly 
than its growing today 
as for last month most economists said the 01 percentage point 
drop in unemployment probably stemmed from a continued tight labor 
market and from the fact that the governments figures based on a 
survey of 60000 households conducted early in march reflected job 
activity in february more than in march 
over the first two months of the year economic growth created 
about 700000 jobs last month based on a separate survey of 
employers just 26000 jobs were added to nonfarm payrolls 
basically 1990 started off to a bang and it seems to have 
come to a screeching halt in march it is troubling but given the 
strength of the first two months im not inclined to panic said 
david wyss of drimcgraw hill 
janet norwood the commissioner of labor statistics said the 
unseasonably warm weather in january and february kept construction 
activity unusually high 
that resulted in fewer opportunities for additional hiring in 
march she said in explaining a 60000job loss in construction 
surging employment prospects in january and february helped 
reduce the number of discouraged workers to 747000 for the 
first three months of the year 
thats a level not seen since early 1979 for all of 1989 the 
number of discouraged workers had averaged 840000 
dederick saw this decline as another sign that were operating 
with an economy than can utilize nearly all of its workers 
discouraged workers are unemployed people who have given up 
looking for a job in the belief that the search will be fruitless 
at the same time the nations manufacturing slump continued 
with a loss of 30000 factory jobs in march that brought 
manufacturing job losses to 100000 since november and 250000 over 
the last year the department said 
theres no indication that manufacturing is going to turn 
around any time soon that sector of the economy is bleeding not 
profusely but its in a recession dederick said 
