<TEXT>
fierce fighting has flared anew in 
this shellshocked border town which has little strategic 
significance but is symbolically important in the war between the 
government and moslem guerrillas 
there is normally little fighting in afghanistan during ramadan 
the moslem month of fasting that began march 27 khost near 
pakistans western border is the exception this year 
the pakistanbased mujahedeen or islamic holy warriors are 
firing artillery from key captured military outposts and pummeling 
the town and adjacent airport 
government forces respond with heavy aerial bombardment to try 
to suppress rebel fire and dislodge the mujahedeen from their 
positions around the mineladen perimeter 
the afghan government in kabul 100 miles to the northwest at 
one time landed three supply flights a night in khost but the 
airstrip is badly cratered and littered with damaged planes and 
supplies are now dropped by parachute 
we are closing in on the communists we have taken the war 
into the city and now we are tightening the circle said 
jalaludin haqqani the most powerful commander in the area 
on the ground we are in complete control in the air the 
communists can still fight and still deliver supplies haqqani 
said in an interview during a threeday trip to guerrilla positions 
both sides have suffered casualties since fighting erupted anew 
last month but exact figures are difficult to determine the 
government rarely releases the number of its dead and wounded 
while guerrilla groups have been feuding for years and dont talk 
to each other 
khost lies at the center of a high plateau in the safed kho or 
white mountains 18 miles from the pakistan border its 
strategic significance is limited but the guerrillas and the 
afghan government have placed enormous importance on the city in 
paktia province 
afghan president najib is from the province gen shah nawaz 
tanai the former defense minister and leader of last months coup 
attempt maintained a home in khost until he defected to the 
mujahedeen 
the town has been on the brink of falling to the mujahedeen 
several times in the past two years but troops loyal to najib have 
always managed to push back the guerrillas 
a week after the failed mutiny tanai boasted to reporters that 
government troops manning the khost garrison would surrender to the 
mujahedeen when he gave the order 
across the border in pakistan the headquarters of the 
ussupported resistance the hezbiislami group led by gulbuddin 
hekmatyar claimed the garrison wanted to surrender but was 
awaiting assurances of safety 
the only major obstacle standing in the way of a surrender is 
jalaludin haqqani said a spokesman for hekmatyar 
haqqani a traditionally proud pathan warrior with a flowing red 
beard is commander of rival hezbiislami faction led by yunis 
khalis 
haqqani has been fighting to take khost since the 1978 coup that 
installed a communist government in afghanistan he is considered 
the most powerful guerrilla commander in the area largely because 
of his wellsupplied fighters and close tribal ties rather than his 
fighting ability 
khalis guerrillas have been blamed for the massacre of some 70 
government soldiers who wanted to surrender to the mujahedeen in 
november 1988 near the eastern city of jalalabad 
their bodies were cut up and put on display and other guerrilla 
groups said that prevented soldiers from defecting once the soviet 
army ended direct military involvement in afghanistan in february 
1989 
on friday moslem guerrillas opened fire as more than 10000 
insurgents surrendered in northwestern afghanistans herat province 
radio kabul said an afghan general a deputy security minister 
and several civilians died in the battle that broke out during the 
surrender ceremony 
haqqanis fighters contend hekmatyars faction has no right to 
negotiate a surrender and say they want revenge for the thousands 
of guerrillas who have been killed during the war 
their stand has enabled hekmatyars guerrillas who have a 
reputation for ruthlessness to promote themselves as 
humanitarians 
the killing of prisoners is unislamic and the koran 
explicitly states that once your enemy lays down his weapons you 
are under obligation to protect him said the hekmatyar spokesman 
before the war khosts population was about 15000 now after 
nearly 12 years of fighting western diplomats in pakistan and 
mujahedeen leaders say that number has been drastically reduced 
they say the only residents are the 5000 to 8000 militia and 
government troops manning the garrison most belong to a civilian 
militia formed by local tribesmen that had supported gen tanai 
throughout the war 
the mud villages between khost and the pakistani border are 
freefire zones and anyone traveling in the area is subject to 
attack by bombing and strafing of afghan warplanes or mujahedeen 
firepower 
the guerrillas fire into the town with mortars recoilless 
rifles and howitzers the bodies of dead are left to rot 
government troops answer with frequent air raids forcing the 
mujahedeen to seek cover in underground bunkers once the planes 
are gone the guerrillas emerge and resume firing 
