<TEXT>
government spent a record 73 billion for 
public school construction in 1987 the third consecutive year that 
construction spending increased by more than 19 percent the 
commerce department said friday 
the departments census bureau said construction spending 
totaled nearly 45 percent of the 166 billion spent in 1987 for 
elementary and secondary education their largest share of total 
spending since 1981 
longterm debt issued for elementarysecondary education is the 
traditional way most school construction is financed in 1987 66 
billion in longterm debt was issued for school systems 
the report finances of public school systems is a 
compilation of all pertinent finance data for all elementary and 
secondary public school systems and local higher education systems 
with more than 5000 enrollment for fiscal years that ended june 
30 1987 with a few exceptions 
total expenditures for all education elementary secondary and 
higher education was more than 246 billion in 1987 the latest 
year for which figures are available 
the federal government spent more than 32 billion or 13 
percent of the total to fund programs such as school lunch and 
milk impact aid education for the handicapped and head start 
federal spending also included education research projects of 
the national institutes of health the department of energy and the 
national science foundation 
states funded almost 140 billion or 56 percent of the total 
spent for education including more than 80 billion for elementary 
and secondary schools and nearly 60 billion for higher education 
local school systems supplied an additional 75 billion or 31 
percent for local public education 
according to the report six states alabama hawaii 
louisiana mississippi new mexico and south dakota received more 
than 10 percent of their elementarysecondary funding from the 
federal government 
local government shares of funding for elementary and secondary 
education ranged from 91 percent in new hampshire to 13 percent in 
new mexico 
new mexico and washington had the greatest proportion of funding 
for schools with the exception of hawaiis stateoperated system 
the report said 
the report said the nation spent an average of 2269 per 
student for instruction in 1987 
alaska had the highest spending for instruction per pupil at 
3721 followed by new york at 3597 and new jersey at 3531 
mississippi had the lowest at 1378 while louisiana was at 1407 
and utah at 1487 
