new warnings will be required on 
overthecounter aspirin products advising women in the last three 
months of pregnancy not to use the products unless directed by a 
physician the food and drug administration said friday 
aspirin late in pregnancy can affect fetal circulation and 
uterine contractions and cause excessive bleeding during elivery 
an fda spokeswoman said 
a thirdtrimester pregnancy warning is already required on 
nonprescription ibuprofen products 
acting fda commissioner james benson detailed the agencys plans 
in a march 29 letter to thomas warriner under secretary of the 
california health and welfare agency 
benson said he was aware of the states interest in preparing a 
similar warning under proposition 65 californias antitoxics law 
and wanted officials there to know fdas plans 
benson said the wording of the warning had not been determined 
but would likely be similar to the ibuprofen warning 
that warning says it is especially important not to use 
ibuprofen during the last three months of pregnancy unless 
specifically directed to do so by your doctor because it may cause 
problems in the unborn child or complications during delivery 
the agency plans to publish a rule on the warning in the next 
several months benson said it would go into effect immediately 
and companies would have one year to make the label changes he 
said 
aspirin labels already advise pregnant women and nursing mothers 
to get the advice of a health professional before using the product 
