bewildered survivors of a predawn fire 
at the residential fontana hotel sat quietly in an emergency 
shelter friday staring dazedly at a crowd of social service 
workers and red cross volunteers 
most of the hotel residents many of them elderly lost 
everything they owned in the blaze that claimed at least three 
lives 
i just sold my business last sunday and moved all my things 
into that room said enid davis a jamaicanborn beautician i 
lost i just dont want to think about it 
i dont have a place to go i dont even have a dime 
ms davis said her children and grandchildren live down 
south in florida but she couldnt remember where she moved into 
the fontana only three weeks ago 
willy james williams 42 remembered coming home from a bar 
shortly before the fire broke out in his room he was startled by 
the smell of smoke that wasnt coming from his cigarette 
when i went for the hall the smoke through the door frame 
caught me full in the face he said a red cross toiletries kit 
in a plastic bag on his lap i lost everything i had 
williams who had been at the fontana for a week said his 
mother lives in miami but i dont want to live with her 
red cross volunteers gently questioned those left homeless by 
the fire paramedics social workers police officers social 
center staff members and reporters filled the makeshift shelter in 
the auditorium of the south shore community center 
