<TEXT>
moslem guerrillas fired on a 
surrender ceremony in afghanistan friday in which 10000 rebels 
were giving up to the sovietbacked government and more than 12 
people were killed kabul radio said the major rebel organization 
jamaitiislami said the surrender was a trick planned five months 
ago to trap government forces 
two afghan generals one of them a deputy security minister 
nine guerrillas and several civilians died in the closerange 
battle that broke out during the ceremony in northwestern herat 
province the official afghan broadcast said 
jamiatiislami islamic society is considered the most 
militarily efficient of the seven pakistanbased resistance groups 
and the dominant one in the herat area 
numerous diplomats based in the afghan capital of kabul and 
foreign journalists were flown especially to herat for the ceremony 
and witnessed the attack the radio said 
western diplomats in pakistan speaking on condition of 
anonymity said they had reports that up to five afghan generals 
were killed or wounded in the 15minute gunbattle and in 
handtohand combat with knives and pistols 
kabul radio made no mention of five generals 
the radio monitored in islamabad reported a small group of 
extremists attacked the welcome ceremony with heavy fire in the 
resulting battle between afghan troops and extremists numerous 
people were martyred 
the broadcast said guerrillas shot and killed lt gen jalal 
razaminda who was also a deputy security minister and wounded 
herat provincial gov fazle haq khaliq yaar as they embraced 
guerrilla leaders who vowed to give up their weapons and join 
president najibs national reconcilation policy 
a second general died later on a military plane to kabul it 
said his identity was not immediately released 
national reconcilation is a term used by the government in which 
local guerrilla groups agree to switch sides and either stop 
fighting or help the government fight the government says tens of 
thousands of rebels joined national reconcilation the past year 
but mujahedeen sources in quetta southeast pakistan said 
fridays attack was first planned five months ago and was 
apparently aimed to avenge a similar attack by government troops 11 
years ago 
according to the sources speaking on condition of anonymity 
the guerrillas slowly began infiltrating the area in november and 
then sent word recently that they wanted to surrender 
the guerrillas known as mujahedeen or islamic holy warriors 
have been fighting to overthrow the government that seized power in 
a 1978 coup and installed a marxist regime the mujahedeen are 
backed by the united states and saudi arabia and are based in 
neighboring pakistan 
according to radio kabul 2200 armed guerrillas and 8000 
unarmed rebels gathered on the plains about 25 miles from herat 
city for the surrender ceremony 
but instead of surrendering their weapons the guerrilla 
fighters turned them on government officials and army troops the 
mujahedeen sources said 
the guerrillas reportedly were armed with weapons ranging from 
side arms to recoilless cannons missiles and rocket launchers 
they fired the first shot as the governor embraced an 
unidentified rebel commander dressed in a white robe and turban 
according to western diplomats and mujahedeen leaders in pakistan 
the governors guards immediately fired back and the plain 
erupted in great volleys of gunfire from both sides they said 
several civilians including children were killed in the 
crossfire that was cut short when two afghan army tanks moved into 
the area and broke up the crowd with bursts of fire the diplomats 
said 
a photographer from afghan national television was reportedly 
shot in the head and seriously wounded 
herat district was the first region in afghanistan to rise 
against the soviet union in early 1979 before the red army 
intervened to prop up the marxist government 
that uprising cost at least 2000 afghan lives when government 
troops pretended to join the rebellion against widening soviet 
influence in the country 
the kremlin pulled out its troops in february 1989 but continues 
to pour an estimated 300 million a month in supplies and weapons 
into kabul 
the leading rebel commander in the district is jamiatiislamis 
ismail khan a former government officer 
herat has been fought over conquered and destroyed since it was 
founded by the persians more than 2500 years ago it was captured 
and destroyed by alexander the great in 330 bc by genghis khan 
in 1221 and by tamerlane a century later 
once famed as afghanistans most beautiful city much of it is 
deserted and in ruins lack of law and order has earned it the 
nickname of afghanistans wild west 
