<TEXT>
most of the murder defendants in the nations 
largest counties are younger than 30 and a third overall are under 
age 21 according to a justice department study released friday 
in fact twothirds of all the felony defendants in those 
counties during february 1988 when the study was begun were under 
age 30 says the study by the bureau of justice statistics the 
average age was 28 
while a third of the murder defendants were younger than 21 the 
study also found that another third were between the ages of 21 and 
29 
the report studied about 11000 felony cases in 39 
jurisdictions and said that sample represented more than 47000 
cases filed in february 1988 in the 75 most populous counties the 
report gave percentages only and did not include the raw figures on 
which they were based 
the most serious arrest charge at the time of arrest was a 
property offense for 36 percent and a drug offense for 35 percent 
a violent offense was the most serious charge for 21 percent with 
murder the most serious offense charged against 14 percent 
approximately six of every seven defendants were male and 95 
percent of those arrested on a murder charge were male 
twothirds of those arrested were known to have been arrested 
previously and about half were known to have at least one prior 
conviction for 65 percent of those with a prior conviction it was 
on a felony count approximately onefifth of all defendants had 
more than one prior felony conviction 
the defendants progress through the system was monitored 
through january 1989 
about 4 percent of all defendants were held without bail 
including 26 percent of murder defendants 
for murder defendants overall 61 percent remained incarcerated 
26 percent without bail and 35 percent with bail which averaged 
75000 for those who remained in jail 
thirtynine percent of murder defendants were released before 
the case was disposed of with 7 percent freed on their own 
recognizance and 32 percent on a financial basis such as posting 
bond bail for those murder defendants who got out averaged 10000 
meanwhile felony defendants with no prior convictions were 
released in 77 percent of the cases compared with 46 percent of 
those with a prior conviction for a violent felony 
the study found that twothirds of all felony defendants were 
released from custody before their case was disposed of 53 percent 
on nonfinancial terms and the rest on bail 
while about threefourths of the released defendants made all 
scheduled court appearances a third of those who did not remained 
fugitives at the end of the study period 
for murder charges 78 percent of those released made all court 
appearances most of those who missed a court appearance eventually 
returned to court but 4 percent of all murder defendants remained 
fugitives after one year 
as for convictions 70 percent of those arrested on all felonies 
were convicted 54 percent for a felony and 16 percent for a 
misdemeanor 
for those arrested on a murder charge 66 percent were convicted 
of a crime of those convicted threequarters were convicted of 
murder 
counties participating in the study were arizona maricopa 
california los angeles orange sacramento san bernardino san 
diego and santa clara district of columbia florida broward 
dade duval hillsborough palm beach and pinellas georgia 
fulton hawaii honolulu illinois cook massachusetts suffolk 
michigan wayne missouri st louis new jersey essex new york 
bronx erie kings monroe new york queens ohio hamilton 
pennsylvania allegheny montgomery philadelphia tennessee 
shelby texas dallas harris tarrant utah salt lake virginia 
fairfax washington king wisconsin milwaukee 
</TEXT>
