<TEXT>
a judge on friday ordered 25 newspapers and 
television stations to give police all film and photographs of last 
weekends antitax riot in london 
a dozen organizations immediately opposed the order two said 
they were willing to hand over what they published and the 
remaining 11 neither opposed nor consented 
judge neil denison issued the order after a day of legal 
argument ruling the film would help police and that it was in 
the overriding public interest 
however he said in other cases the public interest may be 
better served by allowing the news media to report events freely 
and each case should be decided on its merits 
it is right as has been argued that the court should not 
automatically or routinely grant such orders denison said it 
should not be seen to be rubberstamping such applications 
the new organizations reacted angrily 
if we are seen to be a potential arm of the state journalists 
are going to be targets of the rioters said tvam news director 
jeff berliner 
geoffrey shaw lawyer for the bbc and tvam argued there had 
been 2750 police officers at the poll tax demonstration 
they should not require the media to be their eyes and ears 
if they want film it is reasonable to expect them to take it 
themselves shaw said 
shaw said the news media would face increased dangers if all 
reporting material could eventually become available to police 
the riot broke out last saturday after 40000 had gathered for a 
peaceful demonstration to protest the new poll tax by prime 
minister margaret thatchers government 
police were attacked automobiles burned and overturned shop 
windows smashed and shops looted 
police said 339 of the 3000 people who took part in the 
sixhour street battles were arrested police also said 374 
officers and 86 civilians were injured 
scotland yard detective chief superintendent roy ramm who is in 
charge investigating the riot testified that access to all 
published and unpublished film and photographs would help him get a 
clearer picture of the event 
ramm said the photographs taken by police and videotape taken 
from traffic cameras and a helicopter were insufficient 
he said the investigation needed as much material as possible to 
identify people and to follow from pictures their activities during 
the demonstration people pictured in a nonviolent photograph might 
be identified committing acts of violence or damage in another 
ramm said 
the newspapers and television companies ordered to submit film 
include all the major british daily and sunday newspapers and the 
major television companies 
editors have seven days to comply with the orders expected to 
be signed by denison on monday 
