<TEXT>
r dixon herman the federal judge who oversaw 
the vietnamera trial of seven people accused of plotting to kidnap 
henry kissinger has died of a heart attack he was 78 
herman of the us district court in pennsylvania died 
thursday at harrisburg hospital he was admitted march 30 after 
suffering a heart attack said his law clerk bill kellett 
herman was appointed to the federal bench by president richard 
nixon in 1969 and became a senior judge on sept 25 1981 
he presided over the threemonth trial in 1972 of the socalled 
harrisburg seven group of vietnam war protesters which 
included the rev phillip berringan and several other priests and 
nuns they were charged with conspiring to blow up underground 
steam tunnels in washington and kidnap henry kissinger then 
nixons national security advisor in an attempt to bring about the 
end of the war 
the seven also faced charges of interfering with the draft 
board unlawfully mailing threats to kissinger and smuggling 
letters into the federal prison at lewisburg pa 
a jury acquitted the seven of all charges except smuggling 
herman also ruled in a 1979 case that damage claims against 
piper aircraft co resulting from a plane crash in scotland had to 
be tried there 
his ruling was upheld in 1981 by the us supreme court which 
determined that people filing damage claims from accidents overseas 
are not automatically entitled to a trial in this country 
that ruling played a role in determining that the 
multibilliondollar damage suits against the chemical manufacturer 
union carbide should be heard in india where a gas leak in 1984 
killed 3500 people in bhopal india 
herman was a graduate of bucknell university and the cornell law 
school 
he served in the navy in the south pacific during world war ii 
he served an assistant district attorney a state representative 
and county solicitor before being appointed to the bench in dauphin 
county in 1957 
</TEXT>
