<TEXT>
union leaders whove watched the strike lose 
part of its firepower as a bargaining weapon in recent years are 
turning to new strategies for winning better wages and benefits 
the notion that the first thing you do is go stage a strike 
that cry that slogan is dead in the labor movement says bob 
harman of the american federation of state county and municipal 
employees 
the strike used to be almost automatic just part of the 
industrial landscape says john duray of the united mine workers 
now you have unions picking their targets much more carefully 
exhausting all their options first 
the strike has become more of a gamble over the past decade as 
the hiring of permanent replacement workers a practice once 
considered taboo becomes more widespread 
in the ongoing eastern air lines strike for instance the 
company has replaced most of the machinists who walked out more 
than a year ago flight attendants and pilots who conducted 
temporary sympathy strikes also have permanently lost their jobs 
greyhound drivers now face the same prospect in their monthlong 
strike because the company has pledged to give permanent jobs to 
the drivers who join up as replacements 
many labor leaders blame the trend toward replacement hiring on 
former president reagan who fired striking air traffic controllers 
in 1981 the practice has forced unions to look increasingly at 
inside strategies or tactics that workers can use on the job 
to exert economic pressure on employers to win a new contract yet 
also avoid a strike 
tactics include worktorule where employees strictly 
follow work manuals rather than taking their normal shortcuts that 
speed up productivity rolling strikes where workers hold spot 
oneday noshows boycotts of a companys products newspaper and 
billboard advertisements to win the publics support and personal 
approaches to a companys board of directors and shareholders 
all these things can have a tremendous impact on mobilizing 
workers and help increase a unions presence on the shop floor 
says jim green a labor historian at the university of 
massachusetts 
energizing workers keeps them from crossing picket lines once a 
strike starts and can dissaude people from taking replacement jobs 
green says thats what unions did in two of the most recent strike 
success stories pulled off by appalachian coal miners and nynex 
telephone workers in the northeast 
that shows you what it takes to win a strike under current 
circumstances but to say that this is going to be the norm is 
probably expecting too much of the unions green says 
many unions are also devoting more energy to negotiations before 
a contract expires in an effort to head off a strike st paul 
minn county workers for instance called in a mediator to help 
them bargain and as a result were on strike only six days harman 
says 
the communications workers of america is drafting a manual that 
will list 40 tactics organized labor can use to build worker and 
community support and avoid a strike 
in the 1970s nearly 300 strikes involving 1000 or more workers 
occurred each year that average dropped to about 50 per year over 
the past five years federal figures show 
companies have had the legal right to hire replacement workers 
for decades but it was rarely used largely because employers 
feared a public backlash 
reagans firing of air traffic controllers put starch in the 
spine of employers says aflcio spokesman rex hardesty 
twa boise cascade international paper colt firearms and the 
chicago tribune lined up replacement workers before a strike 
occurred hardesty says 
i think it represents the atmosphere that reagan set 
employers are saying well the name of the game is greed and 
weve got the green light its get as much as you can get it as 
fast you can and no matter if it hurts a lot of people says 
afscme president gerald mcentee 
duray says the new age of replacement hiring is disturbing 
from the point of view of what it says about a companys concern 
for longterm productivity and its commitment to its workers 
legislation is pending in congress to ban companies from hiring 
permanent replacement workers in labor disputes 
union officials acknowledge that employers feel more comfortable 
hiring replacement workers because organized labor lost clout in 
the 1980s with a decline in membership 
weve probably been victims of our own success our workers 
may have reached the point where they were making pretty good 
wages had two cars in the garage and they lost that knot in the 
belly a desire to stick together mcentee says 
green says americans also have shifted their thinking on the 
ethics of being a strikebreaker 
it used to be that the worst thing somebody could possibly 
call you in bluecollar neighborhoods was a scab now a lot of 
people think its alright to take someone elses job 
