there is a recession in corporate profits but 
you would hardly know it from the rate at which companies are 
paying dividends compared with other periods its sky high 
good reasons for the situation are hard to find but no harder 
than several other mysteries about the profits recession many 
stock prices seem to have ignored the evidence for instance and a 
lot of forecasters too 
a good many of the published economic forecasts tend to make 
little of the decline choosing to stress instead what they see as 
an improving situation as the year goes on 
a plausible explanation is offered by economist edward yardeni 
when he suggests that if profits fall but the economy continues to 
grow then company managers presumably have a good chance of 
reviving profits 
in contrast says yardeni who does his analyses for 
prudentialbache securities if the economy is in a recession 
the situation is out of their control 
but what about now the decline in profits already is greater 
than that which occurred in the deep recessions of a decade ago 
and officially at least there isnt even a recession under way 
now 
throughout the decline which has lasted four straight quarters 
or since the end of 1988 very few companies have tampered with 
their dividend payout and some of have raised it 
as a result dividends as a percentage of aftertax profits 
following a 16 percent profits decline last year are about 80 
percent whereas a more normal figure would be around 50 percent 
the current percentage says economist h erich heinemann is 
near a record high in the postwar period surpassed only by the 
second quarter of 1986 when the economy skirted the edge of 
recession 
in times gone by the ratio of dividends to aftertax profits 
usually peaked at the end of a recession then fell as profits 
improved but if you can believe uncle sam there is no general 
recession now and none since 1982 
but there is that profits recession and there is no denying 
that a logical tie exists between profits and dividends simply 
stated if you dont make the profits you cant pay the dividends 
however based on experience of the past year that logic seems 
suspended during the 1989 final quarter pretax operating profits 
were running at an annual rate of 2857 billion compared with a 
rate of 3402 billion one year before 
could it be that big bad ugly bear markets in stocks only 
happen if the economy and corporate profits are in a recession 
asks yardeni who believes the economy will continue to grow all 
year long 
in that outlook he has plenty of company among his fellow 
forecasters many of whom see a bigger and better economic picture 
including corporate profits as the year wears on 
it seems therefore that faith in higher future profits is 
having more of an impact on dividends than the current lowprofit 
profits 
what if profits dont rise well it seems that logic eventually 
must prevail that if the money isnt coming in it cant be paid 
out as dividends should the profits fail to recover can dividends 
not fall 
