<TEXT>
the action may be dull and dispirited most 
places on wall street right now but there is a hot new game in 
progress at the american stock exchange 
the excitement centers on a new breed of security scarcely 
three months old that provides investors with a way to play the 
ups and downs of foreign markets most notably the one in tokyo 
these vehicles take the form of warrants which give their 
holders the right to buy or sell another security or group of 
securities at a stated price within a specified period of time 
through their long history in this country warrants have been 
best known as an adjunct to individual common stocks with issuers 
ranging from legions of small companies to such bluechip names as 
american telephone amp telegraph 
starting in january of this year the idea was adapted to 
embrace a stock index in a foreign market specifically japans 
nikkei stock average as the underlying security 
by the end of march amex trading had begun in four different 
put warrants on the nikkei index 
these warrants which constitute rights to sell a cash 
equivalent of a basket of japanese stocks at a set price naturally 
tend to increase in value whenever the going prices of those stocks 
fall 
they have been hailed by some observers as a valuable tool for 
managing and hedging risks that come with the increasingly 
international approach many investors have taken in recent years 
some skeptics by contrast call them a gimmick 
whether for good or ill they appeared on the scene at an 
opportune time as the lofty japanese market ran into a turbulent 
period of selling that drove the nikkei index down more than 25 
percent 
before long the nikkei warrants and a couple of similar ones 
based on the financial timesstock exchange index in britain 
seized a prominent place on the daily lists of the most active amex 
issues 
last week the wall street firm of salomon brothers stirred the 
pot anew with the first of an expected series of call warrants 
on the nikkei for buyers seeking a way to profit from rising stock 
prices in japan 
thanks to that and to rumors of further volatile times ahead in 
tokyo nearly 9 million of the various foreignindex warrants were 
traded on the amex last wednesday accounting for 43 percent of 
the exchanges overall stock volume for the day 
so far this year the warrants have been responsible for nearly 
15 percent of what the amex counts as equity volume 
the speculative allure of this product isnt hard to see the 
first of the nikkei put warrants for instance tripled in price as 
the japanese market tumbled 
among the many risks that also come with these investments some 
are more obvious than others for any speculators venturing into 
this game it is plain that wrong guesses are very likely to mean 
large losses 
in addition it takes market savvy to gauge when a warrant is 
trading at an advantageous price in relation to its underlying 
index on top of that commissions and other trading costs may 
stack the odds heavily against the small investor 
drawbacks like those havent stopped the foreign index warrants 
from attracting a substantial following to date whether they will 
keep growing as rapidly in the future depends partly on what 
happens in the japanese and other overseas stock markets 
should they continue to flourish all sorts of possibilities 
arise for instance could an index warrant or something closely 
resembling it some day provide the springboard to largescale 
index arbitrage and other computerprogram trading on an 
international scale 
if such activity ever came to stir up problems and controversy 
who or what would regulate it 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

