<DOCNO> AP900406-0219 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the bad news keeps coming in the junk bond 
market but that isnt stopping new players from seeking a piece of 
the action 
swelled by the bankruptcy woes of campeau corps us retailing 
arms the amount of corporate bonds defaulting in the first quarter 
of this year quadrupled the bond investors association says 
thirteen companies defaulted on 38 bond issues totaling 569 
billion in the period compared with nine companies and 133 
billion a year earlier the miamibased nonprofit group reported 
the quarters toll surpassed the total for all of 1988 when 497 
billion in defaults were recorded 
the burgeoning growth of defaults is the inevitable consequence 
of the explosive growth of junk bond borrowings in the mid 1980s 
says c richard lehmann president of the association 
were getting that higher fallout because theres more debt 
eligible for fallout lehmann says 
defaults tend to occur four or five years after bonds are issued 
as borrowers problems come home to roost he says those problems 
are plentiful he adds because credit quality deteriorated in the 
80s as companies replaced equity with junk debt via leveraged 
buyouts and recapitalizations 
campeau is a prime example having issued billions in junk bonds 
to acquire allied stores corp and federated department stores inc 
those subsidiaries filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in 
january and accounted for 35 billion of the first quarters 
defaults but even without campeau defaults rose 64 percent in the 
period 
lehmann says he conservatively estimates defaults will hit a 
record 15 billion this year exceeding last years 117 billion 
over the next three years he forecasts a staggering 40 billion in 
defaults 
those numbers may mean bad news for some investors but they 
spell opportunity for fitch investors service inc 
the rating agency has been moving aggressively to compete with 
its bigger rivals moodys investors service and standard amp poors 
and it hopes to make a mark with a new service that evaluates 
socalled distressed credits 
we believe the markets ripe for it says b daniel evans 
chief operating officer at fitch 
in contrast to the traditional rating game which ranks 
borrowers according to their perceived ability to repay fitchs 
recovery analysis aims to tell bondholders how much they are likely 
to get back on investments in companies that are in bankruptcy or 
facing severe distress 
first the service tries to determine the value of a borrowers 
assets then it examines the covenants of the companys bond issues 
to determine what leverage bondholders might have over management 
simple stuff for a rating agency but it gets more problematic 
next fitch estimates how long it will take to work out the 
companys problems and realize values for bondholders then it 
tries to determine how proceeds will be allocated among individual 
bond issues and discounts those proceeds back to the present 
with federated for example fitch estimates holders of the 
retailers senior classes of bonds can expect to receive 78 cents 
on the dollar in about three years time assuming that holds true 
an investor who pays 42 cents for the bonds now would get an 
effective return of 25 percent a year 
fitch is selling its service to institutional investors as part 
of a broad package of highyield research for 10000 a year it 
could be a fertile market judging by the growing number of 
investors poking around the wreckage of the junk market evans says 
oppenheimer high yield fund for example now has 5 percent to 6 
percent of its assets invested in distressed credits compared with 
perhaps 2 percent six months ago portfolio manager ralph 
stellmacher says 
we have gravitated toward that sector because that is where 
were finding the most values he says 
the boom in defaults has been good business for rd smith amp co 
the new york broker specializes in distressed credits and workout 
situations and its staff has grown to nearly 100 from only 30 
three years ago president mike singer says 
it takes a lot of legal expertise to assess the value of a 
bankrupt companys securities because there are no strict rules 
as to how an estate gets allocated singer cautions but for 
those who can do the job theres no end of work in sight 
the supply of distressed securities still far outpaces the new 
funds coming into the market singer says 
</TEXT>
