sciolla new products manager the company declined to release the 
exact sales figures 
we didnt expect it to do as well as it has miller 
spokesman ron richards said we hope the expansion that weve 
done will solve the spot shortages 
the immediate success of sharps did not surprise some beer 
industry analysts who predicted it could soon bump g heileman 
brewing cos kingsberry label as the top selling nonalcoholic 
beer 
frank walters vice president of research for impact a 
bimonthly newsletter for the alcoholic beverage industry said he 
expects growth in the nonalcoholic segment of the market to 
continue 
in 1989 sales of nonalcoholic drinks was up 14 percent he 
said it was one of the fastergrowing segments of the beverage 
market behind imported vodkas up 24 percent and california 
varietal wines up 16 percent 
walters said he expects sales of sharps and odouls the 
nonalcoholic brand anhueserbusch introduced this year to grow 
fastest and put a lot of pressure on la crosse wisbased 
heilemans kingsberry brand 
i think theyll do very well because of the clout that both 
companies have he said 
richards said the overwhelming consumer response to sharps 
was due in part to a brewing process that allows miller to brew at 
lower temperatures minimizing alcohol production 
the process produces a nonalcohol beer that tastes the same as 
regular beer he said 
most other brewers that have nonalcohol or lowalcohol beer 
first brew regular beer and then remove the alcohol along with 
the real beer flavor he said 
richards also cited a trend toward drinking moderation he said 
the product was selling best in the northeast the midwest and the 
west 
the trend toward tougher enforcement of drunken driving laws is 
also a factor walters added 
police arent playing around he said i would suspect 
that onpremise is a big share of the business someone who wants 
to go out and visit a bar they can have two or three and not have 
any problems 
