<TEXT>
financial market turmoil stemming from the japanese 
yens sharp decline provided the backdrop for key talks by us 
treasury secretary nicholas brady and the economics chiefs of other 
major industrial nations who gathered friday 
the ministers from the socalled group of seven nations holding 
their first formal discussions of 1990 also were expected on 
saturday to examine west germanys plans to forge a monetary union 
with east germany as well as the political upheavals in other east 
european countries 
in advance of the meeting at the french finance ministry 
analysts were doubtful the group of seven britain canada 
france west germany italy japan and the united states would 
change course dramatically 
the nations generally work together to achieve broad economic 
goals often through currency exchange rates and rely at times on 
coordinated market intervention as a tool 
i dont expect any major policy conclusions said david 
wyss chief financial economist at the consulting firm of 
drimcgraw hill in lexington mass 
french finance minister pierre beregovoy and his german 
counterpart theo waigel held bilateral talks friday but said 
their discussions did not extend to the international financial 
scene 
the japanese worried about the weakness of their currency 
against the dollar over recent months were expected to appeal to 
their economic partners for help in boosting the yens value 
the yens slump has rattled the tokyo stock market because of 
speculation about its negative implications for the japanese 
economy and stocks have tumbled by more than 25 percent so far in 
1990 
earlier in the week the dollar skyrocketed to a threeyear high 
of more than 160 yen before retreating a bit the yen closed at 
about 1575 yen to the dollar friday in tokyo reflecting 
uncertainty in the currency markets about the outcome of the group 
of seven meeting 
a stronger dollar also is worrisome for the united states 
because it threatens to aggravate the already large american trade 
deficit with japan it makes japanese imports less expensive for 
us consumers and american goods costlier for foreign buyers 
many analysts predicted the united states would be wary of 
promising to do much to prop up the yen some said american 
officials may agree to intervene more in the currency markets by 
selling dollars to try to strengthen the japanese currency 
the japanese would like to see the americans lower their 
interest rates which would in turn help lift the yen but the us 
federal reserve has been hesitant to knock down those rates for 
fear of igniting domestic inflationary pressures at home 
while the financial markets were most interested in the outcome 
of the yen talks the officials could spend more time considering 
the events unfolding in east germany and its eastbloc neighbors 
it will be the first time the finance ministers and the central 
bank presidents have met since the political shakeups in the east 
at the end of last year 
waigel and karl otto poehl the president of the west german 
bundesbank the central bank were expected to give details on 
their plans for creating an economic and monetary union this summer 
with east germany 
the bonn government has become embroiled in a controversy over 
the conversion rate for exchange of the east german currency to the 
west german mark 
the bundesbank has recommended a rate of one west german mark 
for each east german mark with a higher rate for small savings 
accounts 
east germans have complained that the proposed rate would 
effectively cut in half their wages pensions and other savings 
no final decision has been announced on the conversion rate 
the finance chiefs agenda also included plans for the new 
european bank for reconstruction and development designed to 
funnel aid into eastern europe and proposals for increased lending 
by the international monetary fund to poor nations 
