the price tag on the savings and loan bailout 
could hit a mindboggling 500 billion if the economy falters 
congressional auditors said friday in their bleakest assessment of 
the thrift crisis yet 
the general accounting office said it would cost the government 
at least 325 billion to close or sell failed savings institutions 
thats greater than the pentagons annual budget 
but even the new projection a sharp 26 percent higher than the 
257 billion estimate offered by the gao only five months ago is 
optimistic said comptroller general charles a bowsher who heads 
the gao 
it could easily become a 400 billion problem and it might 
even hit as high as 500 billion or half a trillion dollars if 
