a federal jury on friday convicted two wall 
street arbitragers on insider trading fraud and other and counts 
linked to the socalled yuppie five scandal capping a 12week 
trial 
victor teicher and ross frankel both plan to appeal a defense 
attorney said 
teicher 38 who headed the arbitrage firm teicher amp co faces 
a maximum 60year prison term and fines that could total 3 
million teichers firm faces a 500000 fine according to 
assistant us attorney carl h loewenson 
frankel 33 former head of arbitrage research at nowdefunct 
investment house drexel burnham lambert inc he could receive as 
much as 30 years in jail and a 15 million fine 
the verdict ends five days of jury deliberations over a case 
stemming from the yuppie five insider trading case four young 
wall street professionals and a client pleaded guilty in 1986 to 
making illegal stock trades based on inside information about 
corporate takeovers that they had obtained through their jobs 
teicher and frankel were convicted of trading the stocks of 
eight corporations based on stolen information loewenson said he 
did not have a figure for the total profits reaped from their 
trades 
