one night in june 1988 to find a note from her husband 
my dearest kay i have taken my life in order to provide 
capital for you the irs and its liens which have been taken 
against our property illegally by a runaway agency of our 
government have dried up all sources of credit for us so i have 
made the only decision i can its purely a business decision 
you will find my body on the lot on the north side of the house 
mrs council 48 eventually won a federal court ruling that she 
and her husband owed the irs nothing not the 300000 in taxes 
interest and penalties the irs claimed 
the court held the irs deficiency notice was sent four months 
after the statute of limitations had expired 
the irs apparently had misaddressed an earlier notice by the 
time the dispute was decided by the courts mrs council had sold 
her home and paid 70000 in legal fees her credit rating was 
ruined and as she put it i was cheated of growing old with the 
man i love 
she said the poor have little chance of fighting the bureaucracy 
i dont think i would have ever gotten into a courtroom if my 
attorneys hadnt known that i had 250000 from alexs life 
insurance she said 
mrs councils story highlighted a hearing on how the irs has 
responded to the 1988 law aimed at protecting rights of citizens 
involved in disputes with the tax agency 
she has refused to waive her privacy rights blocking the irs 
from commenting on any part of her tax history 
irs commissioner goldberg said the tax agency is doing well in 
implementing the law that requires that taxpayers be notified of 
their rights requires the agency to give earlier notice before 
imposing a lien on property and demands that notices of additional 
taxes owed spell out such claims in clear language 
what the american public resents is complexity uncertainty 
hassles with the irs that take month after month after month to 
resolve goldberg said 
goldberg adamantly denied that the irs has a quota system for 
rewarding employees on the basis of how much they collect he 
called reprehensible a snitch scheme reported to the 
subcommittee in which the irs supposedly would reduce the taxes of 
any business that turned in competitors who were cheating 
it shouldnt be happening goldberg said if it is wed 
like to know about it and will put a stop to it today 
david keating executive vice president of the national 
taxpayers union said that in the fight for taxpayer rights much 
progress has been made but more legal protections are necessary 
he said that even if the new law had been in effect for the 
councils to use it probably would not have helped the provision 
allows a taxpayer to sue for damages if the irs has recklessly or 
intentionally disregarded any tax law but congress dropped from 
the original draft similar recourse in case of careless action by 
the irs 
reckless and intentional treatment is a very difficult 
standard to prove he said 
