<TEXT>
in 1977 a secondtier wall street firm named 
drexel burnham lambert inc issued 30 million in curious ious 
called highyield bonds to help finance the growth of an oil 
company texas international co 
the deal marked the start of the drexel era a corporate cattle 
rush that raised billions of dollars for american businesses 
through risky paper that earned the nickname junk 
investigators say drexels brash behavior also helped spawn 
criminal dealings that sullied wall street in the 1980s 
thirteen years after the tiny junkbond deal drexel is going 
out of business texas international emerges from bankruptcy court 
monday after plunging to a disaster fueled by heavy debts and an 
oil bust 
the relationship between the giant new york investment house and 
the oklahoma city oil driller in many ways tells drexels story 
drexel provided the means to grow temporarily saved the company 
when times soured and now is accused of ripping it off along the 
way 
a report in federal bankruptcy court alleges that drexel sapped 
texas international by trading on inside information secretly 
parking bonds with a scandalous thrift and charging 3 million 
to create a tax shelter for its own holdings 
the 53page report by a lawyer for texas internationals 
stockholders committee unsealed following a request by the 
associated press portrays drexel as hellbent to make as much money 
as possible at its clients expense while serving as financial 
adviser from 1985 to 1987 
while drexel legitimately raised capital for scores of companies 
seeking to grow many of whom still sing drexels praises the 
texas international report supports a darker view of the investment 
firms legacy to the takeoverfrenzied 80s 
there will be the continuing perception that in the pursuit of 
a brilliant idea drexel went too far said samuel l hayes iii 
an investment banking professor at harvard business school 
they were streetsmart people he said they smelled an 
opportunity and moved very aggressively to exploit it they may 
have carried it to the nth degree but thats certainly not out of 
character for an investment bank 
drexel last year admitted to running an illicit trading network 
prosecutors say was directed by junkbond innovator michael milken 
the firm pleaded guilty to six felonies and agreed to pay 650 
million in fines and restitution milken who says hes innocent 
has been indicted but no trial date is set 
drexel was accused of lawbreaking in about 20 deals texas 
international was not one of them and federal law enforcers 
decline to say whether they even investigated it 
the report unsealed by the bankruptcy court nevertheless alleges 
a variety of improprieties and blames drexel for making texas 
internationals problems worse seeking to invalidate drexels 14 
million claim as a creditor the shareholders committee says drexel 
deliberately structured deals to fail so it could generate more 
business 
from 1978 to 1983 drexel issued about 150 million in 
highyield bonds for texas international which used the money to 
expand operations by drilling for deep natural gas in texas and 
louisiana 
in taking on the debt which wasnt limited to financing by 
drexel the company counted on rising oil prices but they 
collapsed in 1986 texas internationals stock fell from 27 to 1 
on the brink of default the company hired drexel to restructure 
its debt by lowering payments delaying due dates and substituting 
stock for some of its bonds 
in three deals drexel refinanced 389 million of texas 
international debt the investment firm pioneered socalled debt 
exchange offers and texas international acknowledges the 
arrangements staved off a bankruptcy filing 
but only temporarily crushed by the burden texas international 
in 1987 sold key oil fields in texas louisiana and oklahomafor 
120 million to make interest payments laying off hundreds of 
workers still failing the company sought bankruptcy court 
protection from creditors in april 1988 
the shareholders report was written by benjamin waisbren a 
milwaukee attorney based on drexel trading records and other 
company documents a federal judge ordered drexel to surrender 
waisbren filed the report last november but asked the court not 
to make it public apparently to try to pressure drexel to drop its 
claim as a creditor drexel whose parent sought bankruptcy court 
protection in february did not contest unsealing the report nor 
has it dropped its claim against texas international 
the report says that because drexel bought so much of the 
companys stock and bonds it blurred the line between paid adviser 
and interested party 
the committee alleges possibly illegal parking with lincoln 
savings and loan association of california a collapsed thrift now 
under federal investigation that bought hundreds of millions of 
drexelissued bonds parking refers to placing securities in 
another partys name to avoid disclosing ownership to the 
government 
the report also claims drexel used inside information about the 
debt exchanges to profit by trading texas international stock 
billed the company 32 million to set up a tax shelter for 
interest income from drexel junkbond holdings and charged nearly 
4 million for financial advice it never gave 
drexel denies the claims 
on each occasion where we acted as financial adviser on 
exchange offers for texas international strong economic benefits 
were produced for the company drexel said in a statement 
based on everything we know the allegations of the equity 
committee are groundless 
the claims were not made by a federal law enforcement agency and 
carry no more weight than a civil lawsuit but they mirror the 
kinds of allegations that have dogged drexel for years 
the common defense among former drexel employees is that wall 
street resented the upstart investment house for creating a wildly 
successful product and siphoning business from established 
whiteshoe firms 
people that couldnt compete just couldnt take it said a 
longtime executive in drexels junkbond department based in 
beverly hills calif 
to be sure drexels crimes and reputation dont tell the whole 
story drexel lent money to chrysler corp when no one else would 
helped mattel corp avert bankruptcy gave mci communications corp 
the power to become a telephone giant 
the people we dealt with at drexel were very creative very 
bright extremely diligent said robert herndon chief financial 
officer of pier 1 imports inc which hired drexel for debt 
offerings in 1987 and 1988 
i think the country has lost something he said drexel 
had a great idea in assisting low investmentgrade companies to 
have access to money that was otherwise not available 
but the texas international report details a different drexel 
similar to the one depicted by federal prosecutors a firm that 
abused securities laws armtwisted clients and manipulated a 
network of junkbond buyers 
the governments investigation showed there wasnt anybody 
they wouldnt cheat if the occasion called for it said bruce 
baird who ran the us attorneys office securities fraud division 
during the drexel case and now is in private practice 
it was sort of the excesses of the 80s personified he said 
</TEXT>
