<TEXT>
the bethlehem steel corp has been fined 
1 million for the continuing discharge of benzene from its coke 
oven operation near buffalo state officials said thursday 
state environmental conservation commissioner thomas jorling 
said the penalty is the largest new york has ever levied for a 
violation of state airpollution laws 
the magnitude of the penalty is justified by the nature and 
duration of the violations jorling said 
state officials said the bethlehem process in lackawanna 
represents the largest single industrial source of emissions of 
cancerlinked benzene in new york state with thursdays fine the 
company has been assessed 133 million in civil penalties since a 
state crackdown on emissions there began in 1984 
we believe that the company acted improperly in allowing such 
emissions to continue in spite of state laws designed to protect 
the air new yorkers breathe said jorling 
the company discharged 15 million pounds of benzene a year 
since the early 1970s state officials said but it was only when a 
team of buffalobased department of environmental conservation 
investigators suspected the discharge and ran tests in 1987 that 
the state first uncovered the problem 
jorling said bethlehem steel knew that its processes emitted 
significant amounts of benzene releases that were subjct to 
state airpollution laws 
after a long series of negotiations bethlehem steel signed an 
order admitting the discharge this week and agreeing to the air 
pollution treatment terms state officials said 
bethlehem steel issued a statement from its headquarters in 
bethlehem pa in which it said it agreed to the settlement to 
avoid protracted litigation 
it will accelerate further improvement sand result in 
completion of the environmental improvement program in 
lackawanna the statement said 
the dec order would require bethenergy the cokemaking division 
of bethlehem and one of the steel giants two remaining operations 
in lackawanna to cut emissions by 95 percent company officials 
have said they already made some process changes that they estimte 
reduced benzene emissions by 30 percent to 50 percent 
bethenergy also was directed to install a closed loop cooling 
system designed to prevent the benzene emissions state engineers 
said the toxic chemical was emitted when water used to cool 
hightemperature coke oven cases absorbed benzene and then was 
later released as the water cooled 
benzene is a flammable poisonous liquid used in paints dyes 
plastics and insecticides it has been linked to cancer in 
laboratory tests 
